                            <strong>üéØ The Genetic Selection Paradox:</strong>
                            <p>Imagine you're a cattle breeder. You select the best bull and the best cow, but their offspring can vary dramatically in genetic merit - some exceptional, others disappointing. This variation is called <span class="highlight">Mendelian sampling</span>, and it had been the "black box" of breeding programs.</p>
                            
                            <strong>üíî Critical Problems:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Unpredictable genetics:</strong> Parent average only tells half the story - individual offspring genetic merit was essentially a genetic lottery</li>
                                <li><strong>Lost opportunities:</strong> Elite animals with exceptional Mendelian sampling combinations were identified only after expensive progeny testing</li>
                                <li><strong>Inbreeding acceleration:</strong> BLUP-based selection was creating genetic bottlenecks, using few elite sires repeatedly</li>
                                <li><strong>Genetic diversity erosion:</strong> Intensive selection was reducing the very genetic variation that enables future progress</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>üö® The Urgent Need:</strong>
                            <p>With genomic selection revolutionizing animal breeding, there was desperate need for methods to:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Predict individual genetic potential before phenotypic expression</li>
                                <li>Quantify theoretical limits of genetic improvement</li>
                                <li>Balance genetic gain with diversity preservation</li>
                                <li>Optimize mating decisions using genomic information</li>
                            </ul>
