                            <p>Cole & VanRaden's genius was recognizing that dense SNP data could reveal the actual chromosomal segments inherited from each parent - the physical basis of Mendelian sampling.</p>
                            
                            <strong>üîß The Two-Boundary Framework:</strong>
                            <div class="method-grid">
                                <div class="method-card">
                                    <div class="method-title">Lower Bound (MSU)</div>
                                    <p><strong>Assumption:</strong> All 43,382 SNPs unlinked</p>
                                    <p><strong>Formula:</strong> Sum of squared differences for each marker independently</p>
                                    <p><strong>Reality:</strong> Conservative estimate - minimum possible MS variance</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="method-card">
                                    <div class="method-title">Upper Bound (MSC)</div>
                                    <p><strong>Assumption:</strong> Perfect linkage within each of 30 chromosomes</p>
                                    <p><strong>Formula:</strong> Sum of squared chromosome-level effects</p>
                                    <p><strong>Reality:</strong> Maximum possible MS variance</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <strong>üéØ Selection Limit Calculation:</strong>
                            <div class="step-specs">
                                <strong>SLC (Conservative limit):</strong> Combine the best haplotype from each chromosome<br>
                                <strong>SLU (Theoretical maximum):</strong> Select the best allele at every single SNP position<br>
                                <strong>Reality check:</strong> True limits lie between these boundaries
